message.content: For any natural number \( x \) greater than 0, the absolute difference between the sum \(\sum_{n=0}^{x} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}\) and \(\frac{2x}{3}\) is less than 1.
For any natural number $x$ greater than 0, the absolute difference between the sum $\sum_{n \in \text{Finset.range} (x + 1)} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ and $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.
For any natural number $x$ greater than 0, the absolute difference between the sum $\sum_{n = 0}^{x} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ and $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.
For any natural number $x$ greater than 0, the absolute value of the difference between the sum $\sum_{n=0}^{x} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ and $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.
For every natural number $x$ greater than 0, the absolute difference between the sum $\sum_{n \in \text{Finset.range}(x + 1)} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ and $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.
For any natural number $x$ greater than 0, the absolute value of the sum $\sum_{n = 0}^{x} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ minus $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.
For all natural numbers $x$ where $x > 0$, the absolute difference between the sum of $\frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ over $n$ in the range $0$ to $x$, and $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than $1$.
For any natural number $x$ greater than 0, the absolute difference between the sum $\sum_{n=0}^{x} \frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ and $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than 1.
For every natural number $x$ where $x > 0$, the absolute difference between the sum of the sequence $\frac{\text{del}(n)}{n}$ over the range $0$ to $x$, and the value $\frac{2x}{3}$ is less than $1$.

For every natural number $x$ greater than 0, the absolute value of the difference between the sum of the sequence $\left(\frac{\text{del } n}{n}\right)$ for $n$ in the range from 0 to $x$, and $\frac{2x}{3}$, is less than 1.
